## Section 3: Security & Resilience

### 3.1 🔴 CRITICAL — SQL Injection via f-string in `build_pre_execution_counts`

**File**: [execution_orchestrator.py:210](file:///c:/Users/ssakesh/Desktop/python/DHARA-GX/Agent%20Dhara%20Backend/agent/etl_pipeline/execution_orchestrator.py#L210)

**Problem**: `cursor.execute(f"SELECT COUNT(*) FROM {safe_table}")` constructs SQL via f-string. While `safe_table` is bracket-quoted, the bracket-quoting logic at line 201-207 doesn't handle **nested brackets** or closing-bracket injection. A table name like `dbo].[; DROP TABLE users; --` would break out of the brackets.

The same pattern exists in [etl_handlers.py:1284](file:///c:/Users/ssakesh/Desktop/python/DHARA-GX/Agent%20Dhara%20Backend/agent/etl_handlers.py#L1284) and [post_etl_validator.py:55](file:///c:/Users/ssakesh/Desktop/python/DHARA-GX/Agent%20Dhara%20Backend/agent/post_etl_validator.py#L55).

**Fix**: Escape closing brackets by doubling them (SQL Server convention):
```python
def _safe_quote_table(table: str) -> str:
    """SQL Server-safe bracket quoting with ] escape."""
    if "." in table:
        parts = table.split(".")
        return ".".join(f"[{p.replace(']', ']]')}]" for p in parts)
    return f"[{table.replace(']', ']]')}]"
```

